FROGS 5 SESSION SHEET FORMAT + TEMPLATE
How to build a GM session file you can run an entire night from, in Notepad.

This governs STRUCTURE. The WRITING GUIDE governs the prose inside >>READ and the
in-world text. Use both. Plain text, hard-wrapped to 80 columns.

The job of a session sheet: one file, opened in Notepad on any machine, that runs
the whole night with nothing else open. Everything inlined. No "see the other doc."


====================================================================
1  HARD RULES OF THE FORMAT
====================================================================

- PURE ASCII. Use -- for a dash, straight quotes ' and ", and ===/--- for rules.
  No box-drawing bars, no smart quotes, no em-dashes. They mojibake in plain text.
- HARD-WRAP EVERY LINE TO 80 COLUMNS. Word-wrap may be on or off, on this machine
  or another; a hard-wrapped line displays the same everywhere. Wrap by hand.
- NO TABLES. There are no columns in Notepad. Related values go on one line,
  separated by " | ". Sub-items indent two spaces under their parent.
- EMPHASIS IS CAPS, BLANK LINES, AND INDENT. That is the whole toolkit. No bold,
  no italic, no color exist here.
- SELF-CONTAINED. Inline every stat block, NPC line, clue, handout, rule, and
  consequence the night needs. A cross-reference is a failure of this format.


====================================================================
2  THE TAGS  (a fixed vocabulary -- the GM searches these mid-session)
====================================================================

Every tag is CAPS and starts a line, so Ctrl+F lands on it. Use only these:

  ## N        Section anchor. Ctrl+F "## 4" jumps to section 4. Number every one.
  WHERE:      Where the scene happens.
  WHEN:       When it triggers, if timing matters.
  >>READ:     Say this to the players, close to verbatim. Follows the WRITING GUIDE.
  GM:         Your eyes only. Never read aloud. What is true, what to watch.
  CLUE:       A load-bearing fact the party needs to move forward. Short. Its own
              line. NEVER buried inside a >>READ or a HANDOUT (see section 5).
  FIND:       A discoverable object in the scene.
  GIST:       The one line you say when a FIND is picked up. Keeps pace.
  HANDOUT:    Full in-world text to hand or paste to the players. Inlined here.
  STAT:       A creature or NPC stat block. Format in section 4.
  LOOT:       What the scene yields.
  IF ... ->   A branch or consequence. "IF they force the door -> Outcome C."
  EXIT:       Where the scene leads. Point at the next anchor: "-> ## 3".


====================================================================
3  THE SESSION FILE, TOP TO BOTTOM
====================================================================

SESSION TITLE -- one line of what tonight is.
One line: "Self-contained. Run the whole night from this file."

## 0  CONTENTS
  A flat list of every ## anchor in run order, so the top of the file is the map.

## 0  STATE AT START
  WHERE the party is, WHO is present (PCs + NPCs + who is elsewhere), the CLOCKS,
  gold, standing rules, and a three-line RECAP of what last session established.
  Keep the recap to a gist; it is a reminder, not a re-read.

## 1 ... ## N  THE SCENES, IN RUN ORDER
  Each one built from the scene template in section 4.

## Z  SESSION CLOSE
  AP awarded, the look-ahead for next time, and OPEN THREADS still live.


====================================================================
4  THE SCENE TEMPLATE  (the repeating unit -- copy this per scene)
====================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## N  SCENE NAME
--------------------------------------------------------------------
WHERE: one line.
WHEN:  one line, only if timing matters.

>>READ: The player-facing description, hard-wrapped, continuation lines
  indented two spaces. Present what is there. No cold, no describing by what
  is absent, no narrating a player's actions or conclusions (see WRITING GUIDE).

GM: What is true under the surface, how to adjudicate, what to watch for. The
  meaning of the scene lives here, not in the >>READ.

CLUE: The one load-bearing line, if the scene has one. (See section 5.)

FIND: <object>  --  GIST: "the one line you say on pickup."
  HANDOUT: the full in-world text, inlined, so you can read or paste it without
    leaving the file. Opt-in depth; it never gates the night.

STAT: <name> ...   (section 4a)

LOOT: item (value) | item (value)
IF <condition> -> <result>.
EXIT: -> ## N+1 NEXT SCENE


4a  STAT BLOCK FORMAT  (inline, pipe-delimited, never a table)

STAT: Draugr Sentinel  x3  (TL1 Expert)
  HP 30 ea | DR 6 | Immune poison/disease/cold | Weak FIRE (x2 dmg)
  Might 17 | Agility 13 | Magic 15 | Guile 8
  Atk Greatsword -- melee, 10 dmg
  Atk Frost Breath -- 15ft cone, 8 cold, Agi TN 15 for half
  Undying Loyalty: at 0 HP drops for 1 round, then rises with 10 HP next turn,
    unless burned or the skull is crushed (Might TN 14, or any fire on the body)

Rules for stat blocks: one line per attack or ability; numbers grouped with " | ";
long abilities wrap with two-space indent. A blank line ends the block.


====================================================================
5  CLUES, GISTS, AND HANDOUTS  (the lore-delivery model)
====================================================================

A lore drop does up to three separate jobs. Keep them separate.

  THE CLUE is load-bearing -- the party needs it to move forward. It must be its
    OWN object: a short CLUE: line, found at its point of use, that you can hand
    over in ten seconds. A clue trapped inside a long read forces you to dump the
    whole thing to deliver one fact, usually at the worst moment. Never do that.

  THE GIST is the one line you speak when a FIND is picked up. It keeps the table
    moving and tells them whether they want to read further.

  THE HANDOUT is the full in-world text -- a journal, a letter, a tome. Inline it
    under the FIND so it runs from this file. Players read it on their own time.
    It is opt-in depth and never gates pace.

WHERE TO PUT THINGS:
  - Load-bearing and must-hear -> scatter it to the point of use, in small beats,
    as a CLUE line. Two short clues at two locations beat one wall in one room.
  - Flavor and depth -> HANDOUT. Trust the table to read; do not force it.

This is the standing fix for the one failure mode: the clue is never in the dump.


====================================================================
6  WORKED EXAMPLE  (the format running)
====================================================================

--------------------------------------------------------------------
## 1  THE KILLING FIELD
--------------------------------------------------------------------
WHERE: Forelhost gate, exterior. The gate stands open.

>>READ: The path crests the ridge and Forelhost sits in the saddle below, black
  stone half-sunk in snow, its iron gate standing open. The ground between the
  trees and the gate is shallow snow over bone: hundreds of Nord dead in corroded
  armor, rotted siege ladders, rusted swords. Three figures pace among them --
  skeletal warriors in Dragon Cult robes, eye-sockets lit blue, walking a slow
  circuit of the gate.

GM: The bones are unmarked -- no army dies clean. Magic TN 12 reads it: poison.
  The cult weaponized its own death; Forelhost was a poison site from the start.
  The Sentinels hold a fixed patrol and do not pursue past the treeline.

FIND: the open gate -- GIST: "the hinges are oiled, used within months."
  HANDOUT: none. It is a tell, not a document.

STAT: Draugr Sentinel  x3  (TL1 Expert)
  HP 30 ea | DR 6 | Immune poison/disease/cold | Weak FIRE (x2 dmg)
  Might 17 | Agility 13 | Magic 15 | Guile 8
  Atk Greatsword -- melee, 10 dmg
  Atk Frost Breath -- 15ft cone, 8 cold, Agi TN 15 for half
  Undying Loyalty: at 0 HP drops for 1 round, then rises with 10 HP next turn,
    unless burned or the skull is crushed (Might TN 14, or any fire on the body)

IF they watch the patrol and slip the gap (Agi TN 14) -> skip the fight.
LOOT: 3x ceremonial greatsword (100g ea) | Dragon Cult Amulet (opens cult doors
  inside; Magic TN 12 to spot what it is)
EXIT: the corridor descends, stale air, a faint sweet chemical smell. -> ## 2


====================================================================
7  BUILD CHECKLIST  (run before a sheet is "ready")
====================================================================

1. Could you run the whole night without opening another file? If not, inline it.
2. Is every line wrapped at 80 and pure ASCII?
3. Is every section a numbered ## anchor, and are they all listed in ## 0?
4. Is every load-bearing fact a CLUE line you could hand over in ten seconds,
   sitting at its point of use -- not buried in a read or a handout?
5. Are all stat blocks inline and pipe-delimited, no tables?
6. Does every >>READ pass the WRITING GUIDE self-check (no cold, no negation,
   no omniscience, no writing the players' actions)?
